Q4. No-load and short-circuit test interpretation (how these parameters are actually measured in practice):
A no-load test on a transformer (secondary open, rated voltage applied to primary) measures: V1=230V, I1=0.15A, P1=18W.
(a) This input power at no-load is approximately equal to which loss component? Why is copper loss negligible in this test? (Hint: what is I1 compared to rated full-load current, say 5A?)
(b) Find an approximate value for R_c using R_c = V1²/P1 (since at no load, nearly all current flows through the magnetizing branch, and P1 ≈ core loss = V1²/R_c)
(c) A short-circuit test (secondary shorted, reduced voltage applied to primary until rated current flows) measures: V1_sc=12V, I1_sc=5A (rated), P1_sc=40W.
Why does this test give you R_eq directly? (Hint: with secondary shorted, the magnetizing branch can be ignored because nearly all current flows through the low-impedance short-circuit path through R_eq and X_eq, not through the much higher impedance R_c||L_m branch)
(d) Find R_eq using R_eq = P1_sc/I1_sc²
(e) Find |Z_eq| using |Z_eq| = V1_sc/I1_sc, then find X_eq using X_eq = √(|Z_eq|² − R_eq²)
